{"source_key":"sha256-564e11a209e70e03f16b9e715ff8b50f","record_index":2755,"record_hash":"sha256:e8c3090e8235aa6f243bda867e6c571cf7c8218f174aa27ad6a1c8e47e5737a2","timestamp":"2026-05-20T17:59:29.608Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"Yes: make transcript storage less raw, then keep named-secret redaction as a tiny backstop. Don’t make the parser heroic.\\n\\n**Findings**\\n\\n1. **Patch now**: [crates/but-agentlog/src/transcript.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/transcript.rs:270), [write.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta/write.rs:128)  \\n   `source_record` is still stored after heuristic redaction. `prune_codex` only removes message content when it is “plain text”, so rich/mixed content blocks can leave raw transcript text in `source_record`. Safer and smaller: after extracting `text`/`tool_input`, remove known content/input/output paths unconditionally, or store a minimal source envelope instead of the redacted raw-ish record.\\n\\n2. **Patch now**: [crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:141)  \\n   Named-secret text redaction misses common quoted-key forms: `{\\\"api_key\\\": \\\"hunter2\\\"}` won’t match because the scanner expects `api_key:[REDACTED:entropy] with no closing quote. It also skips tabs around separators. That leaks exactly the short named secrets this feature is meant to catch. Add optional quote handling + `is_ascii_whitespace`, not a bigger parser.\\n\\n3. **Patch now if touching #2**: [crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:141)  \\n   The scanner matches names inside larger words, so `notoken=abc` / `secretary=alice` become secrets. Privacy-wise that’s tolerable, but it’s brittle and will create weird transcript loss. Require a left boundary and reuse the existing normalized sensitive-key logic instead of maintaining a second name list.\\n\\n4. **Patch now**: [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta/write.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta/write.rs:127), [mod.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta/mod.rs:180)  \\n   Tool results are capped, but `tool_input` is stored uncapped. Agent tool inputs can contain pasted files, prompts, JSON blobs, or env-ish data. Reuse the same cap/drop policy for serialized tool inputs or whitelist compact fields for known tools.\\n\\n5. **Leave**: [crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:78)  \\n   Running named-secret redaction before entropy redaction is fine. The new `TOKEN=[REDACTED:entropy] behavior is more useful than redacting the whole assignment. The issue is boundary handling, not ordering.\\n\\nI didn’t run tests; this was a static review.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T17:59:29.608Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}